135. fere has caused difficulty, Some consider it quite unintelligible, while Conington says it refers to this and the following two clauses, the general idea being ‘that the new colony was nearly settled. A better view is to take sere in a limitative sense with iamque = ⁴ about this time,’ i.e. not insisting on strict accuracy. This use offere is common, especially with words of number, quantity or multitude, with omnis, reliquus, ultimus, and similar adjectives, with such adverbs as semper, and with laic. The expression iamque fere occurs twice in Book v. ll. 327, 8353 while Cicero uses tum sere: ‘just about that time)

subductae : supply erant, and compare 1. 2. The opposite of subducere is deducere, which we have already had in l. 71, where see note.

litore: local ablative.
